# Use Relative Links for Internal Navigation

## Rule
Always use root-relative paths (starting with `/`) for all internal links within the website. Never use absolute URLs (http://, https://, or protocol-relative //) for internal navigation.

## Rationale
- **Consistency**: All internal links work the same way regardless of page depth
- **Portability**: Site works on any domain or subdomain without changes
- **Maintainability**: Easier to update and test locally
- **Performance**: Slightly faster (no DNS lookup needed)
- **Security**: Avoids mixed content issues

## Examples

### ✅ Correct (Root-Relative)
```html
<a href="/discover/screenshots/">Screenshots</a>
<a href="/imprint.html">Imprint</a>
<a href="/download/">Download</a>
<img src="/img/xcsoar.svg" alt="Logo">
<link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/xcsoar.css">
```

### ❌ Incorrect (Absolute URLs)
```html
<a href="//xcsoar.org/imprint.html">Imprint</a>
<a href="https://xcsoar.org/download/">Download</a>
<a href="http://xcsoar.org/discover/">Discover</a>
```

### ❌ Incorrect (Relative Paths)
```html
<a href="./discover/screenshots/">Screenshots</a>
<a href="../download/">Download</a>
```

## Exceptions
- **External links** (to other domains) should use absolute URLs:
  ```html
  <a href="https://github.com/XCSoar/XCSoar/blob/master/COPYING">License</a>
  ```
- **CDN resources** that must be external (e.g., OpenLayers for maps):
  ```html
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/ol/ol.css">
  ```

## Implementation
- All navigation links in `_includes/header.html` use root-relative paths
- All internal links in content pages use root-relative paths
- All image sources use root-relative paths
- All CSS/JS includes use root-relative paths
- Footer links use root-relative paths

## When Editing
When adding or modifying links:
1. Check if the link is internal (same domain) or external
2. If internal, use root-relative path starting with `/`
3. If external, use full `https://` URL
4. Never use protocol-relative URLs (`//`) for internal links
5. Never use relative paths (`./` or `../`) - use root-relative instead
